               <p>PETER COLSON. I am a <rs id="t18260914-126-viclabel745" type="occupation">journeyman baker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-126-victim858 t18260914-126-viclabel745"></join>. I had eleven loaves of bread, and one quartern of flour, in my basket on the 29th of July, about ten o'clock, I left my basket in <placeName id="t18260914-126-crimeloc746">Kirkham-place</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-126-crimeloc746" type="placeName" value="Kirkham-place"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-126-crimeloc746" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-126-off743 t18260914-126-crimeloc746"></join>; I was gone to a customer's about ten minutes, and, on my return, Webb said a man had taken my basket; I went to the right hand, as she told me, and found the prisoner with it on his back - he said a person had given it to him to carry - he had turned two turnings, and was going on as fast as he could walk.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-126-person859">
                  MARTHA 
                  WEBB
               <interp inst="t18260914-126-person859" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-126-person859" type="given" value="MARTHA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-126-person859" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the morning of the 29th of July, I saw the prisoner take up the basket of bread he went away with it; I told Colson, who went and took him - I certain he took it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I met a baker, and asked him if he knew of a situation; he said, not at present; he had two baskets, and I asked him if I should carry one for him - he said Yes, I might take one to the end of Newman-street, and he would give me something.</p>
